Republican strategy of resistance to Obama 's reelection
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center dismisses the latter as a myth, claiming that fraudulent elections in the United States are rarer than deaths from lightning strikes.
In addition, Republican lawyers counted only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in the last ten years.
One thing is certain: these new trends will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions are partly discrediting the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the US states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the US.
That's why most state governments have passed laws since 2009 that make it harder to register or vote.
This phenomenon gained new momentum after the November 2010 elections, which brought Republicans 675 new seats in 26 states.
As a result, in 2011 alone, 180 bills were passed in 41 states restricting the right to vote.
New election laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws reduce the period of early voting, abolish the right to register as a voter on the day of the vote and deprive citizens with criminal record of the right to vote.
Until the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to show a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of a law passed in Indiana in 2008.
Republican authorities quickly extended this practice to other states.
Over the last two years, they've initiated bills requiring voters to show photo IDs in 34 states.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have such a universal identity card as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11 percent of American citizens, 21 million people of voting age, do not have a photo ID issued by their state government.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a document.
The cost of obtaining the required identity card often exceeds $100.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
In fact, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
But that's not all.
Student voters who are considered to be voting for Democratic candidates are not allowed to use a photo ID issued by their school in several states.
But those same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, which vote mostly Republican, to use the voting cards issued by those clubs.
Until 2004, no state required proof of U.S. citizenship to vote.
This was the first time such a requirement was introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the voting of Latinos.
It is estimated that two-thirds of the Latino voters vote for the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers initiated laws in 2011 abolishing voter registration on voting day in eight states.
They also restricted the right of individuals or groups to provide assistance to those who wish to register.
This restriction has not gone without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 election, a campaign to register voters helped put some 10 million people on the electoral rolls.
Meanwhile, the measures taken since 2009 have led to a 17% drop in the level of new voter registration in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in five other states have passed laws aimed at shortening the early voting period.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of early voters were African-American, although African-Americans made up only 13% of the state's total voters.
The same thing happened with the Latin-Americans.
While they represented only 11% of the electorate, they made up 24% of the citizens who voted early.
In contrast, whites, who made up 76% of the electorate, had only 46% of the early voters.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters are actively opposed to passing laws that restrict voter registration.
Several bills were vetoed by Democratic governors.
The most ambiguous laws were suspended by the intervention of the Attorney General of the United States.
This has allowed us to partially limit the negative effects.
For example, only 16 of 34 states have passed laws requiring photo IDs.
However, the new rules that have come into force will certainly make it difficult to exercise the right to vote in the 2012 elections.
Critics from the Democrats have condemned the bias of the laws that have been passed, seeing them as clearly aimed at influencing the results of the 2012 election in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 electoral college votes needed to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the electoral system level will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: these new regulations will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions are partly discrediting the American democratic system.
