The Higgs boson in detail
Last summer, news that scientists may have discovered the Higgs boson caused quite a stir - and for good reason.
This boson is thought to explain the mass of all the particles in the universe, no more, no less.
It's also the last particle predicted by the Standard Model -- our best, or at least "least perfect" description of the nature and behavior of matter -- but it's never been detected experimentally before.
But physicists aren't quite sure that it's the Higgs boson.
We know, without a shadow of a doubt, that we're dealing with a really new particle and that it's very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Moreover, new data presented this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto seems to confirm this, although some data are not yet complete.
But let's say it's a Higgs boson, because the chances of it being wrong seem minimal, and let's see what that means.
There is one law in this world that is absolutely unavoidable, that no two things can be in the same place at the same time.
There's no way around this rule, and don't even try too hard, or you'll hurt yourself.
But even though particle physics is a rather strange world, it turns out that it has one law of its own: the Pauli exclusion principle, which postulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same moment in time if they are in the same "quantum state" - that "state" is, in their common features, in some of their characteristics.
Based on this, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find good citizens called Fermions who are reasonably obedient to Pauli's principle.
In the other, there are bosons, a nasty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything -- at least for that principle, which means they can be in the same place at the same time.
According to the (incredibly unusual) Particle Adventure website at Berkeley Laboratories, these bosons are divided into two groups: mesons, which we won't talk about here, and "force particles", which are the primary forces of nature and are sort of related to the Higgs boson.
These very bosons, it should be emphasized, are not all as exotic as one might think.
In fact, if you're able to read this chronicle, it's because of one incredibly mundane boson: a photon, or "light particle", which is a "courier" of electromagnetic force.
In fact, when one charged particle accelerates or changes direction, it "disrupts" the electromagnetic field at that particular location, like a stone thrown into a pond.
From this "disruption" comes an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and, therefore, one of the "force-carrying" bosons.
More stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, except for that boson to come into existence, another field, the Higgs field, has to be broken.
But the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, you have to reach very, very high energies, like a frozen pond, whose surface can only be shaken by a very large rock.
That's why you need a huge particle accelerator like the one that's being used at CERN -- the Large Hadron Collider, which is a ring with a diameter of 27 kilometers -- to achieve such huge energies.
The electromagnetic field analogy is also useful for explaining the relationship between the Higgs boson and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with an electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, interact, others don't: a sheet of paper, for example, will never stick on the refrigerator.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have mass, while others (like the photon, by the way) don't.
So what can all this research "bring", asks Mrs. Plamondon?
In science, they're used to test the accuracy of the Standard Model (SM), and this also allows physicists to detect discrepancies between the results of observations and the predictions of the SM.
And some of them are eager for such discrepancies to be discovered, because the slightest discrepancy could open the door to "new physics" and plug some of the holes in the Model.
The latter, I have to say, still has significant flaws, offering no explanation for gravity (oh!) or for dark matter, which forms about 80% of the universe (oh-oh!).
But CERN hasn't found any such discrepancies.
The consequences
The benefits of this research for the everyday life of the average person are harder to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that there is none.
Look, back in the early '60s, the pioneers of laser research at Bell Labs couldn't have imagined what a revolution their work would bring.
They envisioned their applications in science, but no more.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the previous ones were pulsed) in 1962, said that the laser was originally seen as more of a "laboratory gadget".
Can you imagine?
And also, there's an app for the study toolkit.
For example, the same William Boyle, in his optical research in 1969, developed a small light sensor.
This sensor, although not at all what it was originally intended to be, is now the "eye" for all the digital cameras in the world and has earned the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This doesn't mean that the Large Hadron Collider will change our lives, of course, but it just shows, in fact, that anything is possible.
Palliative care is the best way to die.
The Quebec Commission for Death with Dignity recently discussed the delicate issue of end of life.
The debate should resume soon, and the bill is being drafted.
However, much remains to be done in this vital area.
"Dog" tried to take a closer look.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Monterey.
Prostate cancer, which had destroyed him from the inside, gave him a two-year deferment.
"I was given five years, I lived seven", he says, between life and death, lying in bed at the Victor Gadboa palliative care home in Bely, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, and you can't prepare for it", he says.
The disease is doing its job: an incredible weakness that prevents you from going to the toilet or even eating on your own.
Sitting at a table with a delicious meal, he gives in and agrees to be helped to eat.
He's got a sense of humor, he's even able to smile, to talk to strangers who work around him, bring him medicine, take him to the bathroom.
Courage in the face of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to be cured of diarrhea, which is humiliating", he admits.
A few hours later, the staff found a cure for the disease.
"We've been taught throughout our lives that a man should urinate standing up", says Pierre Broder, a psychologist at Victor Gadbois.
Regressing to the point of childhood is an unbearable humiliation for some.
"It all depends on the ability of the individual" to cope with decline, he says.
Because, according to many people in palliative care, important events happen at the height of the decline.
The patients who come to Victor Gadboue's palliative care are all cancer patients.
The prognosis is they'll live for three months at most.
At this point, the team of doctors and nurses no longer provides what is called "medical" care.
Mrs. A., 89, fears most of all that she will die "conscious from suffocation".
But the disease has allowed me to get to know my children.
"I have good children", she adds.
"I don't want anything else in life", she says before allowing a breathing mask to be put on her.
She is still waiting for the last visit of her son, who has arrived from Italy, in the coming days.
A group of volunteers provide care and nutrition at Victor Gadboa.
This is palliative care, which is what you get when there's nothing more you can do.
To make it more comfortable to die.
In Quebec, one place in a palliative care facility is needed for every 11,700 residents.
That's not much, considering we're all gonna die sooner or later.
Life here continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christian Martel, one of the hospice's doctors.
Whether it's physical comfort, emotional comfort or mental comfort.
We'll agree to give the dying person a mouthful of brandy or pepsi, whichever he asks for.
We don't make diabetics control their sugar anymore.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we brought beer to Mr. H., who died tonight.
His son finished his beer at the dead man's feet this morning.
"We help our loved ones as well as our patients", says Nathalie Savar, director of patient care.
At Victor Gadboa, no day is the same.
Next to the 93-year-old man enjoying his last meeting with his family in the courtyard, lying on his pillows during a toast in his honor, tragically dies a young man of 36 years, surrounded by parents, wife and two young children and who tried everything to survive.
"In the last six months, three to five beds have always been occupied by cancer patients under 45 years of age", says Dr. Christian Martel, with concern.
53% of patients admitted to Victor Gadboa come from home, and 47% from the hospital.
The problem of access to palliative care
It is estimated that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care that is provided to alleviate the suffering of patients entering the final stages of their life, whether at home, in a hospital or in a nursing home.
And some institutions, like Victor Gadboué and the Greater Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, are more or less exclusively dedicated to cancer care.
It is this huge gap in Quebec's health care system that has many palliative care physicians fearful of passing legislation legalizing euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto has been circulated signed by the brightest in the field of palliative care, Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapuant, and testifying to their disagreement with such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christian Martel, Quebec's health care system is not efficient enough to ensure the right to high-quality palliative care before the transition to euthanasia is authorized.
She says: "I recently saw a patient who spent 14 days in the emergency room in excruciating pain, and no one took the necessary steps to relieve her.
I'm afraid that patients want to die only because they're not getting adequate care.
Meanwhile, many oncologists are working to the last day to save patients despite the pessimistic predictions.
Helen Richard's chances of survival were already slim when she stopped the exhausting chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she told me that she was sorry that I was stopping the fight", she says.
And she told me that my days were numbered!
There is no cure.
Dr. Martel estimates that 90% of patients who ask to die thank the nurses for not granting their request after the palliative care team relieves their pain.
However, it should be noted that palliative care is not the absolute all-powerful way to combat pain.
According to Elsie Monroe, director of palliative care at the Palliative Care Society of Greater Montreal, patients are not sensitive to pain relief in 8% of cases.
At the end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, where the patient sleeps until the moment of death, either occasionally or permanently.
We can no longer pretend that we don't know about these sufferings.
More and more patients who cannot relieve pain will be able to access palliative sedation.
Patients who suffer from pain always say the same phrase: "I want to die".
But it doesn't necessarily mean "I want to be euthanized", it means "I want to feel better".
