Pay and sell without banks - with Bitcoin
The complete opposite of the current money exchange, based on central banks, numbered transactions between the receiving parties and commission fees for processing them.
And as is often the case with these technologies, there is a clear political vision: the belief that the current monetary system, which is based on banking monopolies, is leading to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros ...) and a secure BitTorrent-like exchange protocol that allows for file exchange between participants of one level.
About 200,000 transactions have already been registered from 15,000 computers in the network.
Several thousand websites accept bitcoins for donations or as payment.
The bitcoin price, which peaked at $30 (€23) in June 2011, fell to $2 five months later before returning to about $10 today (the rates are listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing special compared to the global exchange of real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) in its report on virtual currency published in October, was interested in this system.
He describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "competing with the dollar or euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currencies, such as "credits" used for promotion in a video game, which are earned in-game or can be bought (and sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But the exchange operations are always controlled and processed by some central authority.
In Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are simultaneously bookkeepers, auditors, currency issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually happens between two email addresses, like an email.
Only for each new payment can the user choose a different address, thus ensuring anonymity.
The set of information relating to this transaction is signed electronically using a double-key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
The contents of the file make it possible to verify that the bitcoins used in the transaction actually exist in a public ledger that is distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to register the new transaction in this ledger.
It goes through a mathematical problem, sent to the computers, and the person who solves it, like a temporary central bank, gets the privilege of adding this new line.
It's the phase of hashing a file, which is converting a large file into a digital signature, short and unique.
Computers take a new transaction and add a number to it before they hash it all together.
The goal is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (many zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, other nodes can easily check that it's correct.
The transaction is thus inextricably linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification will change the digital signature.
If a user wanted to pay twice with the same money in a very short time (less than ten minutes) for the purpose of cheating, only one of these two transactions would be confirmed by the network - and the other would remain unconfirmed, since they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solves the problem gets 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, the reward is regularly halved, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible by one hundred million, leaving a reserve...
The complexity of the problem also increases with increasing computing power.
The life of the network has had its ups and downs.
Sites that provide Bitcoin services were attacked, and Bitcoin reserves were stolen.
"The flaw is not in the protocol itself", assures Pierre Nouza, who recently launched Paymium, a company that makes payments with real money using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reported the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this disadvantage.
