Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the ledger and found that almost 80% of bitcoin is not in circulation.
The "giant sales" were announced in November.
"Thirty thousand dollars were exchanged", rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works at Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Nouza, another author of the currency manual, believes strongly in the potential of this technology as an operational network.
His system, Paytunia, is the equivalent of a credit card (in real money) or a contactless mobile phone payment, but it uses Bitcoin to verify transactions, which is cheaper.
The owner has better control over his personal data and can thus remain anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for entrepreneurs who don't need to install new devices or software.
Just provide an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by phone, says Pierre Nouza, who assures that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general tendency to overlook hierarchical systems in favor of more horizontal ones.
"It will be some time before Bitcoin is established, but 2013 could be a turning point", he predicts.
The ECB's report proposes, incidentally, to reconsider the various risks which are considered to be high today, should this system succeed.
