The Difficult Births of the Egyptian Constitution
This is another risky move by President Mohamed Morsi.
With Egypt more divided than ever, over the issue of a constitutional declaration that temporarily gives it extraordinary powers, he decided to play the wa-ban.
To everyone's surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on the final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state gave the Assembly two more months to finish the work.
For almost two years, Egypt has relied on a draft text that has been amended several times, which has weakened institutional stability and led to legal conflicts.
This new initiative only exacerbated the division of the country.
According to his opponents, the President persists in his "autocratic delusion", continuing to "break the word" and "trample on the law".
His followers believe that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis and speed up the transition process.
The referendum must be held within fifteen days.
A very short period of time, which forced the Brothers to abandon their intention of explaining to the Egyptians, article by article.
It's also a way for the president to restore public and democratic legitimacy while discontent rages across the country.
Mohamed Morsi seems convinced that Egyptians will vote yes, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Moreover, the call for an accelerated vote is like an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text or I reserve extraordinary powers", which are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
In this strange atmosphere, 85 members of the Constituent Assembly, mostly Islamists, voted for the text yesterday.
Most liberals did not respond to the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they knocked on the door, feeling unable to make their point.
Representatives of human rights defenders, religious minorities or civil society have done the same.
To reach the required quorum, 11 people, the backup participants, were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Not surprisingly, most articles were voted unanimously.
The commentators, by the way, were amused by the fact that one of the few disagreements of the day occurred around... the time of the prayer, as some committee members felt that the hours of the Constituent Assembly were mis-set.
The text, which was voted on yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
The object of public attention, Article 2, ultimately remained the same article from the 1971 Constitution, stating that "the principles of Sharia are the primary source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is one of the main demands, hoped to replace "principles" with "rules", which would allow their more stringent application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a testament to their goodwill and respect for other members of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy", say the liberals, who see it as just publicity.
Because they think the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They point in particular to Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University a consultative role, particularly in checking compliance with Sharia law.
Egypt expert Sophie Pomme said this was alarming because "the people who are called upon to make decisions are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy".
We can see the birth of theocracy".
Many liberals, moreover, are upset that the next president of this university seems to be far less moderate than the current one.
"There is no specific religious intervention at this time.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of civil law.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulama, but people with university education, some of them trained in the French system", reassures Alexis Bloy, who is preparing a dissertation on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he admits that "there may be ambiguity around Article 220, since the terms used in it are borrowed from religious vocabulary.
This applies particularly to "fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence].
And in the future, the question may arise as to how competent civil judges are to make decisions about this".
Apart from its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is criticized as it gives broad powers to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood claims that they have significantly decreased compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another point of contention is the military's authority.
In accordance with the military's wishes, the defense budget will be considered not in Parliament, but in the National Defense Council.
Nor will the military court be banned from prosecuting civilians, despite the pleas of human rights groups.
The latter also expressed concern about the text, which they consider detrimental to freedom.
Blasphemy is still a liability, and insulting is now prohibited, which can have serious consequences for freedom of speech, and especially for freedom of the press.
Furthermore, none of the articles speak about women's protection anymore, points out Heba Moraef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture in Article 36.
A word that didn't appear in the previous Constitution.
