Chief Control and Audit Officer: The check on the schwarz system failed because of the politicians.
The Czech Republic has good control bodies in the public procurement sector and, despite having good legislation, is lagging behind in its application.
This is the statement of Miroslav Kal, Vice President of the Supreme Control and Audit Office, from an interview for Aktuálně.cz.
"The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied correctly, which, in my opinion, we lack", commented Kala on the current situation.
Such conclusions are provided by a joint inspection of the Czech and German control authorities.
As an example of wrong practice, Peter Nechas' approach to the so-called Schwarz system is cited.
The Prime Minister recently said that the GDP will not bother entrepreneurs with checks - is that prohibited or allowed?
"The law should be somehow established, and if it prohibits something, then the prime minister cannot stand in the way of the institutions that are charged with checking and enforcing the obligations", Kala states.
At the House of Representatives' audit committee meeting, you spoke about a joint project between the Czech and German parties, which compared the public procurement legislation of both countries.
What exactly was that about?
I mean, the parallel investigation that we started, like, two years ago.
In other words, European legislation sets out how public procurement should be conducted, followed by national legislation and then also the application in practice.
All the information has been collected and, even with the unfinished check, interesting differences have been found - in simple terms, we may have "accurate and error-free" legislation, but in practice we are inferior to Germany in some parameters.
This means that it is not enough to create more and more precise rules, we need to focus on the application of the law itself.
And how exactly can this project help you, what does it mean to you?
It is this kind of collaborative control that can contribute to efforts to stop the clarification of laws, reduce and improve restrictions, because it does not lead to a positive result.
Economics means getting the right thing for a reasonable (but not always low) price to avoid enrichment and possibly criminal behavior.
But the fact is, we're not going to get there by lowering the order limit.
Perhaps this system will be overwhelmed with paperwork, so that those who want to find loopholes in the system will find them much easier than if the constraint were not lowered.
You're talking about the internal problems of the practical application of public procurement legislation.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there an organization like our CRU, or does it work differently?
As for the institutions, the Bundesrechnungshof is our central accounting office, which is organized according to our principles, and there is also a board that operates in a slightly different way, but basically both institutions function in the same way.
In addition, the powers are similar to a certain extent, but since Germany has a federal structure, there are also audit units at the federal land level - in this their system is somewhat different from ours.
BRH can only manage federal money, we have state resources.
Public funds in our regions and municipalities are controlled at the level of the federal accounting chambers.
As far as the local laws are concerned, are they easier than ours?
I don't want to compare without data, but in some ways Germany is a good example, but you can't say that it's better in everything.
Is it because they're better at controlling?
