Poland and space.
Last week, at a meeting of European Space Agency ministers, Poland was accepted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 September 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with the ESA in 1994 and has taken an active part in a number of the agency's projects over the years.
But Poland's journey into space began much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish enthusiasts were doing space travel, but it wasn't always understood.
I'll remind you, for example, of the lecture of A. Sternfeld, who on December 6, 1933, presented ideas from his groundbreaking work "Introduction to Cosmology" at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory.
The young engineer's ideas left the audience indifferent, and after several years, Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934 in France, he won the Robert Esno-Petri and André Louis Hirsch prize for his "Introduction to Cosmology".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966), mentioned above, later became a great proponent of astronomy and space exploration.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-renowned proponent of space exploration, and his contributions were recognized in part by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the Moon was named in his honor.
Already in 1925, a railway dredge equipped with a rocket engine was built in Poland.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remains unknown, as do the details of the project.
It's not even clear if the rocket was supposed to be used to drive the cart or to slow it down.
The only information about this dress is from the press of the time.
From 1933 the Polish artillery began to think about rocket arrows.
The research was carried out by the Section of Weapons Technology in collaboration with professors Mechislav Wolfke and Gustav Mokzytsky.
The surviving materials show that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the arrival of German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the idea of a photoelectric fighter-missile appeared in the specialized press, which was proposed by engineer Rogozinsky, and the following year the work "Air-based torpedo-missile and aviation-bomb missile" by author Leliv-Kjivoblotsky was published.
Both projects were designed for military use with rocket engines.
Before the war, all projects for the military use of rocket technology were handled by the Temporary Scientific-Consultative Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity, the work was stopped due to the outbreak of war.
The next scientific work on cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Astronaut Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The society was first mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the journal Problems, which published four voluminous articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotic proposed to organize a society that would be engaged in cosmonautics.
At the time, artificial satellite projects were gaining momentum, and it was clear that space exploration was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautics Society (POA) has been trying to join the International Astronautics Federation (founded in 1951), and in the autumn the POA became a full member.
And the following year, the first chairman of the PPA, Kazimierz Zarankevich (1902-1959) became the deputy chairman of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He remained in this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PPA has made a significant contribution to the development of the highly successful RM meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to perform scientific research.
The first RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The missile, capable of covering a distance of 1,800 m, was about 80 cm long, and weighed less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959 two-stage RM-2 missiles were tested in the Bledovsk desert.
This missile was about 1.4 meters long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the missile was already capable of doing real scientific work - the RM-34 missile could cover 14.5 km, and its task was to observe high winds.
But in 1962 further development was halted.
The successor to the first RM-type missiles was the Meteor-1 missile, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The missile was conceived as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm, and the initial weight - 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (designated as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of the camera for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A had a space of 0.4 l, the Meteor-1B - 0.34 l, and the Meteor-1C - 0.62 l.
The maximum range of all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket, with a launch weight of 380 kg, was capable of carrying a payload weighing 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Later versions of Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's accession to KOSPAR (Committee on Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of the national KOSPAR committee two years later.
In addition, within the framework of the Intercosmos program, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Germashevsky became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
