On the one hand, a real political thriller, the so-called "cinema-opus", a story of a successful plot, a scam - an example of this is a series of films about the friends of Ousmane.
The film is constantly changing the mood - on the one hand, documented scenes from Tehran (the titles show iconic historical photographs of events and how the same situations were shown in the film - there are no big differences).
On the other hand, the lighter Hollywood scenes intersect with irony and moderate exaggeration.
And then there are scenes from CIA headquarters and other agencies -- men in suits discussing the situation at the negotiating tables, on the stairs of agencies, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has had a remarkable career reboot.
From a derided actor, he became a respected director, and his acting was no longer the object of ridicule.
"Operation Argo" is his third full-length film, after the dark detective "Goodbye, baby, goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "The City" (2010).
At the same time, it is the first film by Affleck not to be shot in the director's hometown of Boston.
The atmosphere of the place is one of the qualities that elevated the director's earlier films above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck demonstrates this in Argo, where Tehran plays Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place on the streets, when recreating real events - the opening scenes of the embassy fall are impressive in their clarity, which also conveys the emotions of confusion and unpredictability that arise when somewhere suddenly history changes.
Afleck and his colleagues achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (a fake headquarters in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many processes in too many places.
The director had to deal with the fact that the narrative does not involve many exciting scenes of cinematographic significance.
He's pretty successful with this few, sometimes he thinks things up - it doesn't come out so elegantly (the scene where a phone call in America prevents an impending crisis at Tehran airport, and the runway chase looks pretty fancy).
The downside of Argo is the distraction associated with having to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman as their Hollywood co-stars are really charming, but their characters would have deserved more space, and they're not the only ones in the movie.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of drama, it's a film that can be watched with moderate interest, judging by the direction and retro style, recreating the thrillers of the seventies.
But it's hardly exciting.
