Rules of balloon, banana and circus
The www.bankovnipoplatky.com portal, which annually conducts a survey of the most absurd bank charges, has now decided to announce a competition for "the most absurd EU workshop resolution or project".
"We were inspired by the latest event, in which the EU plans to adopt a 40 percent quota for women in the administration of large European companies", said Patrick Nager, the poll organizer, to Pravda.
Among the absurdities already nominated is the recent ruling by the European Court of Justice on the unification of the rates of insurance premiums for men and women.
Until now, women have had a preference for life insurance because they are objectively less at risk to the insurance companies.
"The next incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be submitted to the competition by the end of the year.
The vote itself will be held until the end of February 2013", Nager said.
Controversial EU regulations include mandatory biofuel additions, which are harmful to the environment, a ban on reliable mercury thermometers only because they contain relatively small amounts of dangerous substances, and a cage-size directive for chickens, which has made eggs significantly more expensive this year.
Also criticized was the actual ban on the use of the term "butterbrush oil" or the removal from sale of classic light bulbs.
A good quality banana should be 14 centimeters long.
The European public apparatus often makes decisions under the pressure of a particular trade or industrial lobby, whose positions in Brussels are usually defended by some state or group of states (thus the Czech Republic now defends the demands of its banks even under threat of veto).
The lobby's interests are as follows: for example, the highest quality bananas in the European Union had to be 14 centimeters long and not show "abnormal curvature".
The European Commission has justified itself by saying that it is merely harmonizing existing divergent national rules that have complicated trade.
The EU has eased its standards on fruit and vegetables despite opposition from some countries, citing that existing directives would lead to wasteful consumption.
A candidate for the win in the survey could be last year's EU regulation, which requires balloons sold to be equipped with a warning that children under eight cannot inflate them without adult supervision.
The EU has turned to US studies which show that balloons at play are a potential cause of death by suffocation in children.
A similar restriction now applies to children under 14, who are not allowed to blow in the fairground's dumbbells.
Funny ideas come from home.
The rule concerning European officials themselves is absurd enough: anyone holding any official position in the EU cannot, given the sensitivity of the subject to Greece, use the name Macedonia, and must instead say "BURM" (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
The portal Bankovnípoplatky.com, in cooperation with the association of liberal economists "Laissez Faire", has proposed for the vote, in addition to several of the above absurd rules, for example, the EU rule on the volume of food stocks in the territory of the member state.
The EU has set a maximum amount of food stocks that can be in the Czech Republic on the day of its accession to the European Union.
The Czech Republic subsequently exceeded, for example, the prescribed quantities of canned mushrooms, for which it faced a large fine.
The survey organizers were also interested in the idea of paying some countries for not having a sea, and the idea of granting subsidies for applying for subsidies.
But these ideas came from Prague, not Brussels.
"We are at a disadvantage because we have no sea.
We will ask the European Union for compensation", said the then Minister of Agriculture, Yaroslav Palas (PSDP), in the autumn of 2004.
As an argument, he pointed out that the country had a high grain yield, and as a result of so-called interventionary purchases, the state had full stocks of supplies that needed to be taken out.
For the fact that the Czech Republic is far from ports, the EU, according to Palas, should have paid us hundreds of millions of euros.
As a result, the European Commission went to the Czech Republic to bid for grain from countries that do not have access to the sea.
The subsidy was offered to the villages by the Ministry of Regional Development, headed by Minister Paul Nemetz (US-DEU), in particular, such subsidies were to go to the subsidy application from Brussels.
EU: Fantastic orders are the exception
Although decisions in the Member States are easily criticized, the EU's efforts to regulate and to make the EU more efficient and develop are, in the opinion of many experts, more deserving of recognition.
The serious problem, according to experts, is the drawing of EU subsidies for projects that have no hint of anything to do with deepening European integration, but which the member states have achieved in the budget debate.
It is also a matter of emotion among the Czechs that, like other EU countries, the Czech Republic must fight in Brussels for the right to specific identification of its traditional products, and it does not always win this contest.
Although the Czechs retained the name "Olomoutsk cheese" after six years of fighting with the Germans and Austrians, our producers had to rename "Tuzem rum", whose traditions in our country go back to the 19th century, "Tuzemak".
Only products made from cane distillate can be called rum, not sugar beet.
The official EU list of registered products includes, alongside the world-famous "feta" and "gorgonzola" cheeses, the German Lubek marzipan or Parma radish, for example, Karlovy Vary sausages, Gorzhelyetski and Trzebon carp and Jatec hops.
The EU also has trademarks for Pardubice pepper and Gorjice tubes.
People want me to protect the republic, but I'm an amateur, Okamura claims.
Senator, what makes a man run for president?
I'm not thinking about becoming a senator or president myself.
If we had a smooth run of things in this country, I wouldn't be running for office.
But I can't stand to see the country being robbed over the last 20 years, the thieves running around, people getting their taxes and retirement age raised.
I had no ambition to be a politician.
But when I see something I don't like, I try to find a solution to change it.
And since I'm 40 years old and an independent, non-partisan person, I have no other way to make an impact other than to run for senator or president.
You got into the Senate, but soon you went to the presidential palace.
Do you not turn your back on the people who elected you?
I've been saying I'd join the presidential race depending on the outcome of the Senate election.
I later clarified that if I was elected senator, I would run for president.
My goal is not a position, a position is a tool that I can use to implement my ideas.
So I need the most influence and the most authority.
But the problem is not just that we are a nation that is whining in our bars or watching TV, but we are willing to trample anyone who tries to change anything.
Added to this is the media, which vilifies people and confuses freedom of speech with freedom of lies.
For example, I was said to be a bribe-taker to journalists, or that I was an adviser to Irza Paroubek.
Let's move on to your views.
You started the fight for the presidential palace with a thesis about the financial and criminal liability of politicians and about the return of property declarations for the sum of more than twenty million.
To do that, we need to change the law.
You don't have that kind of power as president, and only the full Senate can propose legislation.
How do you want to solve this problem?
When I lobbied as a citizen to make tourism a free enterprise, it was pushed forward.
The problem with politics is that when someone comes up with a good proposal, left or right, they're deliberately getting in the way, and that's holding people back.
As an independent non-party person, I have much greater potential to win support from all parliamentary parties.
My advantage is that I can take from each party what is best for our country, without party-wide shelving, without dogma-based review, and apply it.
Do you consider yourself more right-wing or left-wing?
From the Czech point of view, I think people think I'm more of a leftist.
It doesn't matter to me if it's a little to the left or a little to the right.
It's important to me that we move forward.
It's not about one being right and one being left, I want to bring people together.
I will always support any good decision for society, whether it is proposed by the CCP or the GDP, and I will also be against a bad idea.
You get angry when someone says you're a populist.
But don't you prove it by what you said?
When you create a business plan for your company, you also have some ideal goals and visions.
And that's what you're trying to get close to.
You might call it populism, but all the proposals I'm talking about are already working around the world, or are being talked about by prominent experts.
But without the support of Parliament, you'll only have slogans.
And you're not going to last long in politics with that.
Or do you think that when you go out and talk to people, you'll be able to implement criminal and financial responsibility?
I don't have any other choice.
Just to convince the politicians, the journalists and the public and try to get them on our side so we can get our way.
If I were elected president, it would not be a problem to organize a live television broadcast in which I would address the chairmen of parliamentary parties, calling for the legalization of financial and criminal liability for politicians, civil servants, judges and prosecutors.
And if they refuse, they'll have to tell you why they don't want to.
If there's a strong person who can voice the abuse, then there's a lot of pressure on the political scene.
Take the direct election of the president - it was the merit of public pressure.
I'm not a genius or an intellectual.
I try to find allies to stand up for my beliefs and views.
I'm just a newbie in politics, and I'm going to try to get a majority for my program.
I'm trying to move things forward on my own; in case I don't, I'll be out of business in six years and back in the private sector.
It sounds a bit like Okamura is supposed to save the Czech Republic.
I'm not a savior.
I know I can't do anything alone, so I've sidestepped a number of prominent people in their bid for the Senate.
I went to Radim Yanchur, he refused because of the volume of work.
I also at least supported investigative journalist Jana Lorenzova, who exposed the light fuel oil fraud.
I ran because people are really unhappy, but I feel like I'm on a scale.
Sixty percent of the people didn't vote, and most of those who did voted for establishment representatives.
We're the only two independents in the Senate.
The people elected the Senate in a way that would make it difficult to make changes.
I'm still going to fight for my beliefs, like direct elections for mayors and governors.
Are you thinking about starting your own party?
I haven't thought about it yet, because I don't have time to go through the cleanliness of every potential supporter's past, and I don't have the money.
There's no money for the presidential campaign, only twenty thousand crowns in my transparent account.
You don't have any money?
You're talking about property declarations, and what about your own business?
His personal fortune is estimated at approximately $60 million.
I have a plot in Prague worth about 25 million, an apartment for 10 million, another apartment for 8 million, an art collection for about 10 million, an Aston Martin for 3.5 million and a Skoda Superb for a million, and several million more on the bill.
And by the way, I got the Aston Martin because it was my childhood dream, and I always liked James Bond, who drove a car, who was a gentleman with women, and at the same time, he fought against the mean and the lawless.
You're driving an Aston Martin, you own a $60 million estate, and you don't have any campaign money?
You say you want to change the republic, but you don't want to put your own money into it.
That's not very convincing.
I don't have 15 million for the campaign.
I'm supposed to go into debt?
I've already put $2.5 million into the campaign.
The fact that I don't have sponsors indicates that my program isn't that interesting.
And I don't have to pay for a campaign out of my own pocket.
My campaign costs are basically covered by my senate salary.
But I wouldn't be able to live on that money, for example, I wouldn't be able to pay my son for English school, which costs 30 thousand a month.
If I was just trying to make money, I wouldn't be running for office.
So you're going to keep doing business for a living?
Didn't you say you were going to cut back on this activity?
But it doesn't depend on the amount of salary.
As I promised, I've partially reduced my activities.
For example, my deputy will be the managing director of a travel agency in the spring.
People would want me to be a penniless man who would preserve the Republic.
But I need to make a living, too.
How much did you get as an entrepreneur every month?
Two hundred to four hundred thousand, and I keep getting it.
And if I were president, I'd end my business.
