MVRDV architects prove that real adventures are not just in the imagination - with the example of Spikenisse and his newly built Book Mountain - 2 photos
"I think it's a fun building, it looks futuristic, we finally have something interesting to see again", says Lisette Verhaig, walking along the edge of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT specialist at a large nearby company, says, "No, this building is really beautiful".
But I ask myself, why do we need another library today?
Everybody has the Internet, iPads and e-books.
Nobody volunteers to go to those old-fashioned libraries anymore, right?
Spekennis, a small sleeping town outside Rotterdam, has an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
To combat this annoying circumstance, a few years ago it was decided to contribute to general education and to build seven imaginary bridges, which are depicted on euro banknotes in the form of picturesque painted miniatures of reinforced concrete.
The success of this educational initiative was modest.
And then the founders of the city realized that they had only one chance left to beat statistics: to build a library here!
Vini Maas of the Rotterdam architectural firm MVRDV, a master of bold column diagrams and the author of witty, sometimes even cynical constructions, took the task with his usual composure and appeared at the 2003 audition with five books under his nose and a smile on his face.
And while the jury members looked around in amazement and shook their shoulders, the bold Maas folded his original gift into a pyramid-sized pyramid and ended his speech in defense of his project with the following words: "Dear citizens!"
So here's my proposal: Book Mountain in the Spikenis, the so-called Buchenberg!
Nine years later, this mountain, worth 30 million euros, has grown.
It is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground garage, a supermarket, a post office and several adjacent residential buildings and townhouses totaling 50 flats.
In early November, the "Book Mountain" was awarded the second prize of the competition "The Best Library of the Netherlands 2012".
The project also participates in the 2012 Dutch national woodworking competition.
Thus, the faceless suburb, which previously had nothing to offer but a postmodern pedestrian zone and a surprisingly ugly town hall, whose white facades suggest a dairy, became richer by one modern piece of architecture.
But most importantly, Spekenis has the first public cultural building in the history of this town.
It 's a long way to the book .
First impression: the Eldorado book under the cheese cap.
There is only one elevator that goes through the middle of the mountain range, so true architecture and reading enthusiasts will prefer to explore the area on foot.
The bright and easily visible glassed room, the burnt brick floors, and the elegant streetlights make for a public city square.
The urban environment is perfectly recreated.
The eye is unwilling to look for benches, dogs, and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere, books, books, books.
"The bookshelves are usually along the facades, and in the middle is a large dark room, usually uncomfortable and faceless", says Vini Maas.
We've put the classic configuration of space upside down and pulled the reading zone from the inside out.
The inner space of the book mountain is used skillfully: offices, an internet library, a chess club, an environmental center and technical premises are located in the center.
The black bookshelves are particularly appealing, as they are used as wall decoration, as parapets, and as staircases.
They are unusual in appearance, texture, and smell.
Even the most sophisticated architects and civil engineers are puzzled as to what this unknown material is.
"We have been working with secondary materials", explains Yop Trauborst, project manager representing the community of Spekenisse, in accordance with the requirements of the standard.
And one day, on an agricultural enterprise in Friesland, we came across a suitable agricultural by-product.
For many years, millimeter-thick artificial fibers have been used as a root cover in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands.
It's cheap and time-saving.
Thin textiles last one or two seasons, then they're thrown away.
For the library, this canvas - the first of its kind - was pressed into panels four centimeters thick.
Under heat and pressure, what is called land-based plastic (KLP) turns into a dark, uniform, durable material that smells a little like a new car and a little like a sneaker.
There are 105 steps to the top.
Those who complete the nearly 500-meter-long trail will be rewarded at the literary cafe not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and wood figs in pots.
They care about the atmosphere, and above all, the proper humidity of the air on the literary mountain.
Costs of a new soul
"It's hard to believe, but this building, despite the many glass surfaces, is an exemplary project in terms of ecology", says Trowborst.
The heat of the earth is used to heat and cool it.
Although the Book Mountain is covered with a glass dome, even on clear days the sun only shines a short time.
The large, glued-wood farms perpendicular to the glass facade provide shade and absorb most of the sun's rays.
The atmosphere is very pleasant.
The rest of the protection is provided by fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the above-mentioned IT skeptic, has already visited the new library.
Lisette Verheig has been here before.
And a teacher of traditional Chinese medicine, Cynthia Bogard, who called Buckenberg "the Spykenisse soul that has long been missing".
The reason: A few weeks before the opening, each resident received an invitation to donate one book from his or her congregation.
These books were to fill the empty shelves of the library, which at that time had 70,000 books, and which was not yet fully completed.
It worked.
The shelves are on top.
"There is nothing worse than a half-empty library", says architect Vini Maas.
"I think that with our invitation, every resident is now connected to this new home in some way.
Everyone knows his book is part of this building.
Even if it's only for decoration.
So MVRDV has solved the royal challenge, which in professional jargon is called identity creation.
Spikenisse wrote his literary history.
And they're very young and uneducated.
It's just a starting point for building identity.
Szabo: "The Germans must play a more important role"
Germany abstained from the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
According to Stefan Saba, an expert on U.S.-European relations, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic path by doing so.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany first made it clear that it would vote against the Palestinian request for observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained from the vote.
Why? Why?
Stefan Szabo: Germany does not support the Israeli actions in Gaza.
Germany needs to be careful about its special relationship with Israel now.
But at the same time, I don't think she supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without being too critical of Israel.
During the March 2011 uprising in Libya, Germany also abstained from voting on the introduction of a no-fly zone.
NATO finally made this offer.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yes, it is.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, that is, it is moving from a policy that was, so to speak, led by the United States, to a German foreign policy.
The situation is further complicated by the fact that Europeans lack a coherent policy.
So the Germans are again caught between two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they're just beginning to feel their role, but they're on their way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
The kind of foreign policy that France or Britain has.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from the German perspective?
It's a willingness to take a position in their national interest that is independent of the position of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, that is, on exports and ties with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are very different from those of other major states, and Germany must therefore protect its own interests.
Did these economic interests influence the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote at the UN?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf states.
So she needs to be careful not to offend the public and the elites in Arab countries.
Either way, it does play a role.
But I wouldn't put too much emphasis on it, it's not a completely one-way connection.
But in any case, it's a big part of the Germans' calculations.
Has Germany harmed its relationship with the United States by abstaining from important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I'm sure that in Europe and even in the US, there is a prevailing understanding of the German position.
So I don't think it was as dramatic a setback as the Libyan issue.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect.
This signals that it should be taken seriously as a player on the international stage and that its interests should be taken into account.
There are different opinions in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
The United States, on the other hand, has been very clear about the veto.
Is there a difference of opinion between the United States and many European countries?
Because of American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama administration has a deep understanding of the European position.
But given the local political situation, the government cannot, of course, openly take that position.
I believe that the significant differences in opinion are not at all as significant as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you'll notice that Obama is not at all happy with Netanyahu's policies.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the United States on the one hand and its position as the most important partner in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would have been a little easier for the Germans if there had been a single, uncontroversial European policy, but that's not the case now.
So they can't act within the larger framework and are forced to act instead, based on their own vision of the situation.
That's what they do with the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will take the lead in the development of a common European position.
It's not easy for Germany, at least not because of its ties with Israel.
That's always been a sticky subject.
But I think the Germans understand that they have to play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, will it not take on a truly leading role?
Or is the lead still hard for Germany?
Germany is not yet used to this, it is still always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it is still always difficult to play a significant role.
Take the euro crisis, for example, and every time Germany takes on a major role, there are all kinds of anti-German sentiments.
The Germans can't handle this easily.
Actually, it's an old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
Germany is in a much worse position than the United States in this respect.
She has to take into account the different neighbors and opinions, which is not easy.
So, the US influence in European politics is constantly weakening, but at the moment the EU is not filling that vacuum, so who is left?
The Germans will just have to play a bigger role.
Even if you don't like it, it's unpleasant or it makes you feel more unloved, that's life!
Steffen Sabao is the deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institution where academics and political experts from Europe and North America collaborate to explore the issues facing the transatlantic community.
In addition, Szabo is a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Trademark protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani is a world-famous brand, and Polo Ralph Lauren is.
But what is an Armani Polo?
It's a completely official Chinese name, which has nothing to do with the companies that it's based on.
However, it will be protected until the original owners file a lawsuit.
But even then, it's not clear if they'll be able to defend their rights.
"Foreign trademark protection in China is becoming increasingly difficult", says Thomas Patloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing, which specializes in trademark infringement in the Far East.
Every week, a new case of this kind comes up on my desk.
Imitators can only add a few letters to their trademark registration.
So Gucci is Lu-Gucci, instead of Prada you can register Prada-Kny.
German companies, such as sports goods manufacturer Puma, are also legally copied in the same way.
Patloch opens a folder with the records of the trademark registry office in Beijing.
On September 14, 2010, the Chinese company registered the Zegna DF Puma trademark, an artificial name that also used the name of the Ermenegildo Zegna fashion house.
The fact that the Chinese are the world champions in copying and infringing on intellectual property is well known.
In large cities, there are department stores that sell almost exclusively counterfeit goods.
But Patloch's case is not that, and he has been instructed by his trustees to oppose the idea of Chinese companies officially receiving from the Trademark Office the right to use a name that is already protected elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "ban min pai", the passenger brand.
This word is associated with "ban dakwan".
That's what they call women who hunt rich men.
Chinese authorities have not admitted guilt
"It's damaging to business, and we need to fight it", Patloch said.
"The brand is being blurred, the unique position is being lost, the image is suffering greatly".
Financial losses and legal costs in affected industries are in the millions, especially in the case of expensive copy products.
According to market research company CLSA, China is the third largest and fastest-growing luxury market, with annual sales of 15 billion euros.
However, it is difficult and expensive to remove questionable trademark records.
The trial could take up to nine years, with an uncertain outcome.
Pattloch tells of cases in which the court dismissed claims, as after a long time the contested name became "a reality of the market".
If the plaintiff is unlucky, he may even have to pay the plagiarist for damaging his trademark in China, Patloch says.
Sometimes it's the law of the jungle.
There are also famous cases of graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a lawsuit against construction machinery maker Sany, which had recently acquired concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
So the Chinese still have the right to use a logo that looks like a Mercedes star.
The company that bought Volvo, Geely, initially used a blue-and-white logo that resembled BMW; the process was successful, and Geely had to change it.
Fashion maker Lacoste lost in China to imitators from Hong Kong and Singapore, who had the famous crocodile looking the other way.
The Chinese authorities do not consider themselves to be responsible.
The CTMO Trademark Office in Beijing confirms that in 2010 there were difficulties due to the lack of personnel and equipment in the premises.
But last year saw "a return from a work emergency to normalcy".
For example, the number of unresolved objections has decreased by 22 percent.
Nearly 57,000 such cases were closed, 75 percent more than last year.
However, 81,500 claims are still pending in the department.
It 's costly to fight it .
As is often the case in China, the numbers are impressive.
Last year, the CTMO received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
This is a record and means that China has topped the list of new registrations worldwide for the tenth time in a row, the ministry reports.
The same goes for the total number of valid trademarks, which is only 5.5 million.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan in fees were paid.
Simply put, this means that each registration costs an average of 1280 yuan, or 160 euros.
It costs many times more to protest, as the case of the German family-owned company Freudenberg shows.
For more than seven years, the concern has been fighting a Chinese plagiarist.
The Germans succeeded in eliminating the illegal manufacture of their counterfeit automobile parts.
However, the imitator secured the Chinese rights to the Freudenberg trademark.
This was a mistake of its own, since surnames are not protected in Germany, says Hannö Wentzler, chairman of the board of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
And the CTMO trademark office has rejected the Munich claim.
True, Freudenberg won both subsequent instances, but the opposing side continues the fight to this day.
We need to be vigilant
The matter is currently before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler hopes to bring the case to a successful conclusion and praises the professionalism of the courts.
But he also says: "The process is extremely expensive and takes a lot of time, money, and nerves".
Internal costs are hardly accounting, the firm's archives have had to go through even records from a century ago to produce evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg unsuccessfully offered the opposing side a "big six-figure sum in euros" for settlement.
"It's clear how much it costs us", says Wentzler.
The dangers of the Far East threaten to spread even to Europe.
That is, if the impersonators register unprotected trademarks there.
For example, one Chinese manufacturer in Germany wanted to register the name Freudenberg for shoes and leather goods.
The company has long since stopped production in these areas, but it has managed to prevent registration.
"You have to be on your guard", says Wentzler.
Both he and Patloch advise German companies to be very careful with China.
Rather than relying on international trademark protection regulations, foreigners should "register in China everything that is worth protecting in any way", Wentzler says.
