However, this was not done to prevent people from getting to work from the suburbs, but to prevent protesters from getting to the parliament building.
On Sunday, Mexico's new leader Enrique Pena Nieto will wear the presidential dress and assume the reins of government.
He has a difficult task ahead of him.
Mexico has enjoyed good economic performance under the administration of Felipe Calderón, who is now in office, but the country is mired in a war on drugs that has already claimed some 60,000 lives in six years.
"My government declares to the people of Mexico its readiness to fight violence", Mr. Peña Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office of the White House earlier this week.
I'm going to propose a new security strategy that will allow us to achieve that goal.
Before making such statements alongside the US president, Mr. Pena Nieto's political career was spent as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In his homeland, the densely populated and vast state surrounding the nation's capital, opinions about the new leader were divided.
A straight man .
In the idyllic town of Valliere de Bravo, for example, he is fondly remembered.
The residents credit him with reviving tourism, developing the resort sector and creating infrastructure.
The city can be reached by one of the new highways built by Mr. Peña Nieto, which are very different from the roads with ditches and holes that were previously on this site.
His name is displayed on the modern sports center and the impressive interactive museum dedicated to climate change.
"We are hopeful of real and serious change", says his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, a state congressman from the institutionalized revolutionary party (PRI) led by Pena Nieto.
We expect real and decisive changes that are so urgently needed in our country, first and foremost in the areas of security and economic development.
After 81 years of continuous rule, the PRI was ousted in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olvera admits that after his 12-year absence from the Los Pinos presidential palace, the party has high hopes for Enrique Pena Nieto.
He also denies the accusations of incompetence that the opposition has leveled against the new president.
He's very forthright and very committed to his vision of the future of the country.
He's a great statesman, and above all, a man who can listen.
But in another part of the state, many people have a different idea of the former governor.
The municipality of Nessaualkoiotl, also known as Ciudad-Nesa, is the most striking contrast to the paved streets of Val-de-Bravo.
Hidden beneath the highway ramps, it is in many ways a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the municipality are also the harsh nature of this metropolis.
Earlier this year, troops were deployed to quell drug gangs in these areas, where violence against women is particularly acute.
In the last two years alone, dozens of dead women's bodies have been found in the desert near a vast landfill.
More than a thousand women were murdered in Mexico State during the governorship of Mr. Peña Nieto, far more than in the notorious violent city of Ciudad Juarez, which has become a household name when it comes to the murder of innocent women.
According to Mr. Pena Nieto's opponents, he was at best unable to deal with the problem of female murder during his tenure as governor.
At worst, his administration is accused of ignoring the problem completely.
Resident of a concrete house, like most homes in this run-down neighborhood, Irina Buendia barely holds back her tears as she shows me pictures of her dead daughter, Mariana Luna.
According to the official version, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes that she was killed by her roommate.
"When I got to her house, it was as if her body had been washed before", recalls Mrs. Buendia.
There were signs of beatings, and the body was already decomposed.
Mariana tells the story, and her daughter's portrait looks at us from the wall, where it hangs next to a crucifix with just one word written on it: justice.
That is what they said was denied to this family.
"State officials treated me like an old gossip, a discontented troublemaker.
They want people to just take what they say for granted and keep quiet.
But that's not right, that's not right, especially when there's so much wrong and wrong around", she says.
By wearing the presidential dress on Saturday, President Pena Nieto will be taking on a difficult responsibility with her.
Tens of thousands of families in Mexico have been affected by violent crime over the past six years, and the new president has promised to make addressing this problem a priority during his tenure.
"I hope he will be exactly the same president as he was governor", says Olvera, a congressman from Valle de Bravo for the PRI party.
But that's what the families of the victims in Ciudad Nesa fear most.
Bradley Manning has not complained of ill-treatment, prosecution claims.
Prosecutors are trying to refute Bradley Manning's claims of poor conditions in detention.
The hearing focused on Manning's time in military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense is demanding that the case be closed on the grounds that Manning's conditions were harsh.
A U.S. Army private is accused of stealing several thousand classified documents.
On Friday, the prosecution sought to prove that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest classified material leak in U.S. history, failed to take advantage of the many opportunities to file a complaint about the mistreatment he said he had endured while in military prison.
During cross-examination at a pretrial hearing in Fort Meade, Maryland, military prosecutor Major Ashden Fein stated that records of Manning's weekly visits by prison officials during his nine months in Quantico, Virginia, contained no complaints of ill-treatment.
The cross-examination of the defense's motion to dismiss Manning's case on the grounds that the conditions of his detention were cruel and in themselves sufficient punishment was held the day after Manning stated that while in custody he intended to commit suicide.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of stealing several thousand classified documents while serving in Iraq.
These materials were later published online on the WikiLeaks website.
WikiLeaks did not confirm that the source was Manning.
During Friday's hearing, prosecutor Fein, along with Manning, reviewed the reports that were filed after Manning's visits by administration officials during his time in Quantico Prison, where he was in strict detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
During visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When prosecutor Fein asked about the reports on Friday, Manning admitted that he judged the prison administration's treatment of him as "excellent" and the general conditions of detention as "very professionally organized".
The reports contain no complaints of ill-treatment, despite Manning being asked directly about the conditions of his detention, Fein claims.
Manning responded that he had expressed verbal concerns about these problems and that the administration representatives who visited him had discussed these problems with him and stated that they would address them, but had not recorded this in writing.
"They recorded 'no problems' (after my complaints were discussed), but that doesn't mean I didn't bring it up in the conversation", says Manning.
A military judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not complained of his mistreatment in January 2011 during a committee hearing on suicide intentions, which he had expressed in writing several months earlier.
Manning responded that during that hearing he wanted to have his "trauma prevention" regime lifted and his prison conditions relaxed.
Military officials explained that the restricted detention regime - a level lower than the suicide prevention surveillance regime - was introduced to protect the prisoner, as well as for the safety of others.
"I wanted to let the administration know that I was fine, that they would cancel the injury warning regime... that my standard of living would improve, from my point of view", Manning explained.
On Thursday, Manning testified that he was arrested in Iraq and transferred to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the Naval Base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said that he had thoughts of suicide in Kuwait, and that he had fainted one day in the heat.
He explained that it's very difficult psychologically when you're not told how your fate is decided, and what's going on in the outside world.
"My world has shrunk to the size of Camp Arifjan, to the size of my prison", Manning said Thursday.
- I thought I was going to die in this cage".
While in Quantico, Manning, he said, spent most of his time in a small cell - at least 21 hours, and often even more than 23 hours a day - completely alone.
Manning reports that he was only allowed to leave behind a mattress, a blanket, a pair of slippers, a few items of clothing and glasses.
He says he tried to move because sleeping or even just lying down during the daytime was forbidden by the rules.
Manning said that while he was sleeping, he was constantly struck by light from outside the chamber.
If the guards didn't see his face when he turned in bed at night, he said he was woken up and made to turn his back.
Manning's attorney filed a formal objection to Manning's wrongful treatment in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to the military prison at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
In addition, on Friday, the judge questioned Manning about a statement he made during testimony Thursday, that after being forced to sleep naked in his Quantico cell one night, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other inmates at a morning check-in.
Manning said he couldn't cover himself with a blanket during the inspection.
In response to questions from the judge on Friday, Manning said he understood from the guard's order that he should drop the blanket he could cover himself with, but admitted that no one had specifically ordered him to drop it.
On Thursday, Manning said he was forced to sleep naked the night before because he tried to show the officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reported that he told the officer that he could have used a rubber band or a strap to injure himself, but he didn't.
That night, according to Manning's testimony, his underwear, his slippers and his glasses were taken from the cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account what he has been through while in detention and significantly reduce his sentence if Manning is found guilty by a military court, which is scheduled to begin hearing his case early next year.
The defense has said it plans to offer Manning a plea of guilty to lesser crimes and challenge other charges as excessive.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend, and the prosecution is expected to insist that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was held at Quantico under the rules governing the detention of detainees with the strictest possible regime.
Manning is charged with aiding and abetting, unlawful facilitation of the Internet, transmission of information relating to national defense, and theft of government property or documents.
If convicted on all counts, he could face life in prison.
My national crisis is the story of a Mexican-American.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico due to the lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who left because they remind the people of the country's difficult times.
Ruben Navarrette believes that Mexican-Americans are torn between two cultures.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I walked down the arrivals corridor, approached the border control zone, and I stopped.
Signs pointed to two queues: one for Mexicanos (Mexicans), the other for Extranjeros (foreigners).
I stood in front of them for a few seconds, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in central California, and I've been called Mexican all my life.
It's just a conventional name, like my friends in Boston call themselves Irish, and my friends in New York call themselves Italian.
Later, I stopped at the complicated construction of "Mexican American".
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, in my grandfather's homeland, there was no need for conditional names or complex constructions.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask questions or answer them.
But my vocabulary is poorer than that of native speakers, and I can't shake the American accent.
So I got my American passport and I got in line for the Extranjeros.
I remembered this story a few days ago when the newly elected president of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House and met with President Obama.
The agenda for the meetings of these presidents was the usual issues: immigration, drugs and trafficking.
President Peña Nieto spoke eagerly about the rise of the Mexican economy, which would now allow Mexicans, with the same success, to stay in Mexico instead of moving to the United States.
He wants to make a partnership agreement with the US and Canada and create some kind of North American trade bloc like the European Union.
In addition, President Peña Nieto promised to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, but no specific proposals were made.
For Mexico, relations with the United States are a difficult and old-fashioned matter.
Most Americans never thought that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and under the gunpowder of rifles forced its leaders to give up half of their territory.
But Mexicans think in centuries, not minutes, and they see reminders of those events in everything.
So, if any U.S. official speaks a word of criticism of Mexico, the press and the Mexican elite are immediately complaining that the Americans are encroaching on the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the descendants of Montessori are filled with war.
But the most complicated is Mexico's relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States.
You want to talk about the hurt?
There's enough of them.
In Mexico, there are winners and losers, people who find opportunities in this country, and those who don't.
There are so many people of Mexican descent in Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver, or San Antonio for one reason only: at some point in their family history, someone -- their father or grandfather -- didn't have the opportunity to make a living in Mexico and had to go north.
Mostly they were Mexicans of a certain type -- the dark-skinned, the low-educated, the poor peasant families.
We're their descendants, and we remember that.
Mexico sees it differently.
Today, our lives are the American dream, we went to good schools and got good jobs, but we must not forget that even that dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national self-determination is confused and vague, but we know what country to call our own.
The United States of America.
And we also know that most of the Mexican elite and ruling class don't like us.
We answer them the same.
They see us as a reminder of humiliating defeats and treat us as second-class citizens, as not-true Mexicans.
We don't speak Spanish well enough, and our ties with Mexico aren't strong enough.
They think we're a failure.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
We would not be behind the silk curtain, finding a satisfying life in the United States but losing our spiritual ties.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and legally moved to the United States as a child, and it reminds me that there's some friction between real Mexicans and Mexican Americans -- Mexicans have a clearer sense of their national identity, and Mexican Americans are offended by that.
She's a U.S. citizen and she thinks she belongs to both countries.
At the same time, many of the Mexican-Americans I know don't feel like they belong to any of them.
We listen to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we also love Bruce Springsteen.
You get the best of both worlds, you inevitably lose your roots.
In Mexico, we are Americans.
And in the U.S., we're called Mexicans.
Now, as I found out during my trip, as if our relationship is not already confused enough, some Mexican leaders and intellectuals want to re-establish relations with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to be a kind of ambassador for Mexico and represent its interests in the United States.
We could tell our American friends about what a beautiful country this is and how great it is to visit, and we could convince political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yeah, of course.
It's not gonna work.
Too many grievances in the past.
And given the gap between rich and poor, the rampant corruption and drug trafficking, many of us don't think this country is so great.
Sorry, but you're on your own, amigos.
And that's only fair.
If a section of Mexicans still cannot forgive the United States for what they did to Mexico a century and a half ago, they will have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans are still resentful of what was done to their relatives in Mexico more recently.
I know.
I think we have more in common than I thought.
Old Battles in the New Middle East
The ceasefire agreement between Israel and Hamas could be a fragile foundation for future peace
Is a lasting peace possible between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East?
Another round of bloodshed leads to the conclusion that such hopes are futile.
The sound of the senseless arguments over who started it is familiar; many buildings are in ruins; over 140 Palestinians, mostly civilians, and six Israelis have been killed; for the first time in the conflict, rockets fired from the Gaza Strip have fallen in the vicinity of Israel's capital, Tel Aviv, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But while Israelis and Palestinians are hopelessly locked in their age-old conflict, the Middle East is changing.
There are many ways to look at this, but the events of the "Arab Spring" have turned many established realities into a storm of rebellion, and Palestinians and Israelis have been unable to stay out of the vortex that has shaken the region.
Perhaps as a result, their struggle will be even more bloody than before.
But there are reasons to hope for a way out of this deadly stalemate.
A war without winners
At first glance, the situation does not seem to be optimistic.
Even if the ceasefire agreement signed on November 21 is upheld, the clashes this week have only strengthened the positions of the security forces on both sides.
The leaders of the Islamist Hamas movement, which came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, say they forced Israel to retreat despite the casualties they suffered.
Despite the fact that some of the group's leaders have been killed and 1.7 million people are trapped in one of the most densely populated and troubled parts of the planet, Israel has failed to eliminate Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is growing in popularity in the West Bank, another Palestinian territory now controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well conclude that time is on their side.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grows, Hamas has new powerful and wealthy friends.
The emerging regional leader Turkey, once Israel's closest ally among Muslim countries, has come out in support of Hamas; it has been followed by Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamically developing states in the Persian Gulf.
Hamas's solemn supporters are declaring an Islamic crescent around Israel, from Lebanon in the north, where the militant Hezbollah group rules, to Syria, where increasingly pro-Islamist rebels are about to overthrow Bashar al-Assad, and on to Jordan, where the king's government threatens Hamas allies.
The most significant shift in the balance of power in the region occurred at the southern borders of Israel, in the most populous and important Arab country, Egypt, where the Muslim Brotherhood's influence was strengthened under President Mohamed Morsi.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was ousted in 2011, was a secular dictator who paid little attention to supporting Hamas.
The Muslim Brotherhood, by contrast, is an organization much like Hamas, with their leaders more inclined to populism.
In future diplomatic settings, Hamas could become a major player whose voice cannot be silenced even by Israel and America.
At the same time, the hardliners in Israel will come to the opposite conclusion.
Hamas was defeated militarily.
The Israeli Iron Dome missile system justified the cost of its creation and successfully destroyed many of the Hamas missiles launched.
The citizens of Israel can sleep peacefully, at least for a while.
As for diplomacy, the US has remained steadfast; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for the latest round of violence.
Another important factor is Israel's economic prosperity, especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, which largely ignored the peace process.
Although approximately 30 Israelis have been killed by rockets fired from Gaza since 2004, Israel has managed to minimize the problem of suicide bombers, in part by building a wall that encircles the West Bank - a large part of the unrecognized Palestinian state - and protects Jewish settlements that continue to expand despite the illegality of such actions under international law.
Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party - in preparation for the January 22 elections - has joined forces with even more aggressive conservatives led by Avigdor Lieberman, is in a very comfortable position.
What's the point of helping the Palestinians and giving them their own state?
If you give them all the power in the West Bank, won't they start firing missiles at Israel from there, like their brothers in Gaza?
Better to keep them behind the walls and stifle any attempt to raise their heads.
The hardliners may win, but their calculations may be disproved by the Arab Spring.
While the Islamists who are coming to power in Egypt and elsewhere have a rather lukewarm view of Israel, their priority will be domestic issues.
Israel's defense budget is bigger than all of its Arab neighbors combined.
Warfare with a regional superpower is unlikely to help Arab governments strengthen their own economies.
The pragmatism of Egyptian President Morsi, who worked with Barack Obama on a ceasefire, is a good sign and could mark the beginning of change.
Israel, no less, must consider the long-term consequences of its policies.
As democratic change in Arab countries unfolds, the deprivation of Palestinian self-determination is a time bomb that will sooner or later explode in the Israeli-occupied territories, like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression is already undermining the foundations of the democratic order in the Jewish state, and the demographic aspect - the Arab population growth - is only exacerbating these problems.
The bloodshed that occurs every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress Hamas has been paid for with growing international discontent.
Both sides need outside impulse.
The only solution that remains is what the sane representatives on both sides, and much of the rest of the world and our newspaper, are calling for: two states and the Israeli surrender of territory in exchange for security.
There is hope, not too great in the short term, that a ceasefire will allow other countries to influence the parties to the conflict more effectively.
Egypt, which has long since decided to cut off arms supplies to the Gaza Strip, and Turkey and Qatar are more than ever in a position to persuade Hamas to recognize the boundaries of the Jewish state, agreed since 1967, with the exchange of territories and the shared use of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries should also make efforts to reconcile Hamas and Fatah.
This would do more for the creation of a Palestinian state than the upcoming UN vote, which could result in the virtual recognition of a Palestinian state.
President Obama must play his part in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he never presented his own peace plan.
Now that he's back in the White House, he's still showing a reluctance to get involved in the solution.
That's a catastrophically short-sighted position.
The United States has a vital interest in stability in the Middle East.
This is only possible if there is a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
In Australia, a uniform cigarette packaging law has been passed.
Warnings about smoking and images of diseased parts of the body are contrasted on dull green boxes, identical for all brands of cigarettes.
The first ever Australian law on the uniform packaging of cigarettes and tobacco products came into force, replacing the logo and colour scheme of different brands with the same dark olive-colored box with gruesome pictures of diseased body parts and images of children whose health is undermined by their parents' smoking.
Apart from the different pictures and inscriptions warning of the dangers of smoking, the only difference between the packages, which has been mandatory since this Saturday, is the names of the stamps, which are printed in the same small type.
These are the harshest conditions in the world for tobacco packaging.
The Australian federal government says that the goal of the measure is to keep young people from smoking by stripping the harmful habit of its fashion status.
The basis for this decision was the results of studies that showed that people who did not start smoking before the age of 26 never became smokers in 99 out of 100 cases.
"It is clear that even at a very young age children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to convey through the design of the packaging", explains Minister of Health Tanya Plibersek, referring to studies that have shown that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated with the idea of a princess in children.
Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world, so these changes won't affect the profits of multinational corporations much, but other countries are already considering similar measures.
Tobacco industry officials strongly opposed the law.
Tobacco companies claim that this will only increase their share of the black market, where cheap and affordable cigarettes will be sold.
"This law will have serious consequences, different from those envisaged by its initiators", says Scott McIntyre, a spokesman for British American Tobacco in Australia.
Counterfeiters from China and Indonesia will be supplying much more of these goods for sale on the streets of Australia.
For some, on the contrary, new laws are a boon to business.
Sandra Ha of small family-owned Zico Import Pty Ltd argues that the demand for cigarette butts and silicone cases that hide unpleasant images on the packaging has grown rapidly (from almost zero) since companies like British American Tobacco, British Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost a case in Australia's High Court two months ago, where they tried to appeal the law.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already sold about 6,000 products to wholesale businesses and is expecting a new batch.
It's a good business for us.
A potential obstacle to the effectiveness of such measures is, according to experts, the popularity of social networks among the very segment of the population targeted by these measures.
After a series of laws in Australia made it illegal to advertise cigarettes on television and to support sports events, and to prohibit sellers from displaying cigarettes in public places, tobacco advertising moved to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned local companies and websites from advertising online, but it cannot restrict foreign sites.
"If you sell tobacco products and you have only this one tiny loophole left, the idea of promoting your product online will seem very tempting", explains Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman notes a rise in brand reviews written by supposedly ordinary users on social media sites like YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
The question is, is it really the work of a common man who loves Marlboro cigarettes so much that he spent his time and effort making a video, or is it the work of a marketing company?
British American Tobacco's Australian division claims that the industry is more concerned with adapting to the new regulations than with advertising.
Tobacco industry officials have even sponsored Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules, which have filed complaints with the World Trade Organization that trade has been unfairly restricted, despite the fact that all of these countries have very little trade with Australia.
A decision by the WTO is expected by mid-2013.
According to Tanie Plibersek, the government has been discussing with other countries the possibility of adopting similar packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada was the first country to mandate the posting of photos warning of the dangers of smoking.
This rule is now adopted in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey, and Ukraine.
Tougher laws are being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many smokers in Australia are demonstrating defiance.
These pictures don't bother me.
I'm just not paying attention.
"You just take out a cigarette and put it in your pocket", explains Victor El Haig, who buys cigarettes with a picture of a mouth tumor on the pack.
Honestly, the only thing that could make me quit is my little girl.
James Yu, the manager of King of the Pack, a tobacco store in downtown Sydney, says that the same packaging has made it difficult to get products on shelves
"It used to take me an hour to unload a new batch, but now it takes me four hours", he complains.
"If the government had to take over and ban cigarettes altogether, we would have said, 'What are we going to do, it's over, we're closing the store,'" he says, raising his hands.
Boredom in a world of electronic networks and constant connections is not so bad.
On Thanksgiving, I had to spend five hours at the airport because our plane had a mechanical problem and was replaced by the other plane we had been waiting for.
So I had plenty of time to think about the nature of boredom.
I won't lie to you.
Half a day at the airport waiting for a flight is really boring, and there's not much help here from books, magazines, iPhones, or even duty-free shops.
Recently, however, more scientists and child development specialists have spoken in favor of boredom.
They say that in certain situations, for us and for our children, being bored is not so bad.
It forces the brain to focus on interesting, interrelated topics, which may help creativity.
And because we're all in front of screens all the time in the modern world, the benefits of boredom are missing.
Maybe we should strive for boredom?
- I know.
And at the same time, no.
We'll come back to that.
I used to think, like many people, that boredom was a relatively recent invention, when people had more free time.
This is not the case, says Peter Tui, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary, Canada, and author of Boredom: A Lively History, Yale University Press, 2011.
"Boredom actually has a very long history", he says.
On the walls of Pompeii, Latin inscriptions about boredom have been found dating back to the first century.
But the question remains, how do we understand boredom?
The problem, says John D. Eastwood, an assistant professor at York University in Ontario, Canada, is that the understanding and perception of boredom has often changed.
After reviewing research on the subject and asking a target group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the following definition: Boredom is when people "want to do something that would give them satisfaction but cannot".
The difference between boredom and apathy, he says, is that a bored person does not do something he would like to do.
You don't want to do anything when you're apathetic.
The main cause of boredom, he says, is "attention disturbance and the associated mood swings and the feeling that time is running slowly".
The description of boredom can seem very similar to depression.
But Professor Eastwood argues that despite the possible connection between these conditions, bored people see the causes of problems in the world and circumstances, whereas people experiencing depression see the problems in themselves.
Sometimes we think we're bored, when in fact we just can't concentrate.
In their study, "The Unoccupied Mind: Defining Boredom in Attention", published in the September issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues refer to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a recorded voice reading a journal.
Some participants also heard loud sounds from a non-relevant TV program in the next room, others heard the same sounds at a low volume so that they could hardly be distinguished, and a third group listened only to a voice recording without a third-party soundtrack.
Those who listened to the TV at a low volume reported being bored more often than others -- they had difficulty concentrating, but they didn't know why, and they attributed it to boredom.
When we try to concentrate on a difficult or exciting task, interruptions can be boring, says Mark J. Fenske, assistant professor of neurology at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when we are doing something uninteresting, "like looking at a flow of goods on a conveyor belt in search of marriage, distracting music can help us avoid boredom".
He goes on to say that when people start to swing on a chair or draw curls on a piece of paper, they're supposed to do it out of boredom, but now we know that actually doing these things is just to help you not relax physically.
"The study found that children who were not told to sit or roll learned better and remembered more than children who were told to sit or roll", says Professor Fenske.
At times, we all get bored: when a flight is delayed (as in my case), when we listen to a monotonous speech, when we watch a film that is not interesting.
However, different people display different degrees of boredom.
In the 1980's, researchers developed a "boredom-tendency scale" to measure such individual traits.
The scale is based on questions and statements such as, "A lot of the things I have to do are monotonous and monotonous", or, "I have too much to do, so I don't have time for anything".
Using questionnaires like these, researchers have found that boys are more likely to miss girls, says Steven Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially when faced with a variety of external stimuli.
However, teenagers in general often feel bored.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of personality and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he paged nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day.
And what he found was that 32 percent of the teens said they were bored at school and doing their homework, and 23 percent said they were bored outside of school.
Only three percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson notes that he has no data on what the data on boredom would be like now, 21 years later.
However, he knows that "the teenage years are the peak of boredom", largely because children and adolescents are not allowed to make full decisions about what they do.
So back to my original question: Is boredom useful?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, research shows, it can lead people to engage in absurd and dangerous physical activities, risky gambling, or the abuse of certain substances in an attempt to get rid of boredom.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have pondered the connection between boredom and creativity, says Professor Vodanovich, who has spent more than two decades studying the problem.
"This is how our brain tells us to do something else; this is boredom", says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
But that same brain doesn't always know what it's best to do.
If you get bored and you turn that energy into playing guitar or cooking, you're doing yourself a favor.
However, if you watch television, you will only get better for a while, and soon it will pass.
So if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he will stop being bored, but he will not learn to cope with boredom on his own or to manage his time and schedule in any other way", says Professor Fenske.
