The hardest job in the world: the miners from Kavah-Ijgen
For four euros, Indonesian miners risk their lives and health to haul 70 kilograms of sulfur to the top of a volcano along steep rocky trails
Some people find their job hell, and others literally work in hell.
Among them is Anto Vijaya, one of 400 miners who earn a living by mining sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, located on the eastern island of Java, Indonesia.
Each day, Antho descends to the bottom of the crater, where sulfuric gas rising from the Earth's interior freezes in contact with the air.
He picks up huge pieces of sulfur, weighing up to 70 kilograms, and puts them in two bamboo baskets, puts them on his shoulders, and carries them up the steep, rocky road.
The summit of the 2,386-meter-high volcano is only 250 meters [2,500 feet] away, but it takes over 40 minutes for the weary loaders to climb up with a tortoise-like stride, struggling to balance and carefully navigating the path to avoid tripping over and falling off the cliff.
They know that one wrong step can cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell off the cliffs of Cauvaux-Igneux a few years ago.
The miners from Kavakh-Ijgen earn 5 cents for every kilogram of sulphur they extract
Once at the top, they make their way through the tourists, who photograph them as if they were monkeys from a circus, and, tired of carrying heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the scales that the mining company has placed just above, at an altitude of 1,850 meters.
This is Kandy Ngrimbie Pt., the company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, not to mention, its workers, who are paid 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) for each kilogram of sulfur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to petrochemical companies, since the mineral is common in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite, and even to bleach sugar.
"Since the norm is to carry 70 kilograms, we earn about 46,000 rupees [$2,500] per move", explains Antô, who usually does three carries a day.
He spends three hours on each one and feels broken at the end, but they allow him to save 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) by the end of the day.
While it seems a pittance for such an inhuman effort, it's three times what he would have earned in the field.
"The daily wage for miners is very high by local standards, with a daily coffee harvest of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) and an average monthly salary of two million rupees (167 euros)", explains a truck driver who used to work as a stonemason on the tourist island of Bali.
There his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the plot was not that heavy, but Antô returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a good reason that in Indonesia is as crushing as the shit: "I married a girl from Bali, where there are only Hindus, and brought her to Java to convert to Islam".
Anto has asthma, he's having trouble breathing, coughing all the time, and his eyes are watering from the toxic gases.
At the age of 27, Antô spent three years risking his life in Kavakh-Ijgen, which had already started to affect him despite the presence of a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, he's having trouble breathing, he's coughing all the time, and his eyes are watering from the toxic gases that the volcano is emitting.
It's the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
"I'll work for two more years because I want to open a shop or learn Spanish or French", he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished for life, this pleasant and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, a waiter, or a hotel janitor, but instead he is doing the work of a mule.
Sharing a dirty wooden hut with other porters, he gets up every day at two in the morning because the sulfur keeps leaking at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the darkness.
Defying the shadows, Antô descends into the crater, lighting his way with a small lantern attached to his helmet, which he himself bought with his own money.
About 400 carriers carry sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the volcano
Despite high profits, the mining company has not mechanised sulphur mining to save costs and does not provide any equipment to carriers who work on their own account and with such deprivation.
In fact, they don't even get a cut of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) photo fee, which, along with the 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) entrance fee, the park guards charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"This is a job for livestock, not people", says Badrusin, a 42-year-old hard-working porter who has spent three decades in Kavah-Ijgen since leaving college.
Capable of lifting up to 110 kilograms, he says he will endure the work "as long as he can", because he needs money for the education of his three children, ages 18 to 10.
I'm not retiring, I'm dying here, because the volcano is my whole life.
Although the sulfur burns their throats and burns their eyes when the wind suddenly changes and catches the miners in the dense columns of smoke coming out of the volcano, they are so resilient that none of them complain of their severe illnesses... more serious, obviously, than their usual breathing problems, arthrosis, knee pain and ulcers on the shoulders that have deformed under the weight of the baskets.
By balancing the basket on his back, Unaynik can now lift only 50 kilograms at the age of 53.
