"It's a very secret thing, my mom may know it, but not the whole world", he claims.
I upload beautiful pictures or pictures from games to FB.
I also have fun with my friends.
"I wouldn't share a photo that wasn't mine or someone who was acting stupid", he says.
The boy realizes that it is wrong to post indecent photographs of naked people, crimes, or to write offensive or angry comments.
Jorge claims to know 35 of his FB friends and 9 of his Twitter followers.
Most of them are related.
The mother knows, she has a password to one of the accounts.
I started Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if they're answering me, I'm just uploading them", he adds.
"Social networking is a form of entertainment, and I can talk to distant relatives or friends quickly", he says.
Without hesitation, he says that he would never accept a request from a stranger.
Wouldn't count on someone to recommend him to a stranger.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
This teenager has open accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space, and Ask, and in the latter admits that he doesn't know the 20 people added to his friend list.
"It doesn't scare me, because we have something in common, like music", he points out.
According to the boy, no one had confided in him or asked for his home address or phone number.
"If they start pressuring me or demanding something from me, I just delete them", he admits.
Jose became an Ask follower after reading the recommendation on Twitter.
The boy was no stranger to what is now known as cyber-mobbing.
A friend of mine was blackmailed on social media.
He was threatened and extorted money.
"He never knew who it was", he assures us.
The victim, according to Jose, didn't delete the account.
"Just turned on privacy".
Then it explains the sequence of steps to configure the account in a secure way.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of people he knew in uncomfortable or confusing situations.
Yeah, I would if I didn't like the person or if I wanted to.
"Although I know it's cyberbullying", he confirms.
The key questions
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and an expert in education and learning, believes that to guide children and adolescents, one must understand that the purpose of social media is to inform.
"The Internet was born as a means of finding information, but with the advent of these sites, the rules of the game have changed", she says.
Porras points out that academic Mark Prensky, a Yale University master of education and author of Digital Aborigines and Immigrants, coined these terms to explain this phenomenon.
Digital Aborigines are them, the children and youth who were born in the age of technology.
"We are digital immigrants, who have to teach them while we are still learning", she says.
She explains that this topic is difficult, "because we ask them to have a certain criterion of what they can or cannot distribute, publish or speak at an age when they are not mature enough to do so".
"Also, they should be selective, whereas being popular, having thousands of friends, is what matters most to them, regardless of the consequences", she adds.
He says that the most effective way to teach children and teenagers about privacy is to ask questions that make them think.
"It's useless to tell them not to do it", she adds.
Porras then lists some options: there are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why do you do it online?
Or would you like to have a photo of you posted like the one you posted about your friend?
Do you know what others are posting about you?
When you sign pictures from a party, do you ask other people's permission to mark them?
And one more thing, does everyone need to know what you're doing at all times?
Another point is to make them understand that they should behave online as they do offline.
The rules are the same.
"Offline, people behave with respect, responsibility, and other principles, and so should social media", she says.
The Watch
Eduardo Guardia, a university lecturer, elementary school professor, and education consultant, explains the need for family heads to read social media policies conscientiously.
By understanding each of these points, they have a good basis for discussing with their children the prerequisites for opening an online account.
"For example, age and what is allowed to be distributed or published", he says.
According to Gaurdi, the key is to remind children of the lesson "don't talk to strangers".
UNASUR summit ends without the Lima Declaration
The 6th Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) concluded today in Peru without the release of the Lima Declaration, announced earlier and theoretically signed by the seven binding participants.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VI Regular Meeting of the Heads of State and Government of UNASUR, however, sources from the Office and the Presidential Administration indicated on the main page that it will be transmitted after the closure, but then confirmed that at some point it will be published on the website of the Peruvian government.
When asked about the text, they pointed out that the content was laid out by Peru's president, Olliante Umal, during a brief statement to the press.
Access to the Summit was always restricted.
During the day, only a video of the presidential assembly without sound was broadcast in the press room with the message "closed session, no sound".
The little information that circulated among reporters was given by the press secretaries of some UNASUR governments that were present at the meeting, but not the Peruvian one.
The only document circulated during the day was a list of participating presidents, which provoked the displeasure of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media outlets who asked for more information.
Subsequently, the Peruvian presidential administration sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was a statement by Umala, not the official document that ended the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South American and Arab Countries (ASPA), and this time, despite press press pressures, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had been announced earlier, was not circulated.
The official ASPA website verifies that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to ensure that all journalists had access to the media, but they limited the access to information to the maximum extent possible.
The summit also ended with Chile and Peru jointly deciding to accept the Hague Court's verdict, which would settle the territorial dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Olliante Umala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at a regional meeting and ratified that they will abide by the decision of the International Court of Justice, which begins Monday in The Hague hearing the statements of both sides, as part of the indictment that Lima has brought against Santiago.
"We will respect and enforce a decision that clarifies the differences we are currently presenting to this international court", said Umala, standing next to his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and will be a country that respects international law, peaceful resolution of disputes, pacts and international tribunals", added Pinera, and greeted Umalu with a handshake on the background of the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they will submit to the International Court of Justice came after Colombia this week protested the Bogota Pact, which recognized its compliance with the court's verdict following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua that it considered to be wrong.
The summit was held in the absence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chavez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Christina Kirshner.
Paraguay, whose membership in UNASUR was suspended in 2011 after the impeachment of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollianta Umala, was responsible for opening the discussions in the morning and closing the summit a little later in the afternoon, Lima time.
The head of state read the final document, in which he said that 16 agreements were adopted and 31 projects were approved among South American countries, the amount of the proposed investments amounted to 17 billion dollars.
Among the agreements he mentioned were that UNASUR countries would take "important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding residency agreements".
He said that action was being taken to improve "cooperation in the fight against citizen uncertainty and organized transnational crime, action to increase access to medicines, affordable Internet access in all parts of South America and to address the risks of natural disasters in a collective and effective manner".
With Europe in crisis, "economic integration (of Latin America) should not be triumphant, but should serve to expand our manufacturing base and foresee a better future for our cities", added Umala.
"We have decided to give privileges to a group of 31 landmark projects that will improve the connectivity of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas... uniting our countries and forming new economic schemes", the Peruvian president said in a message read.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five are related to Peru, and are limited by transverse axes in its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two are aimed at greater connection with Ecuador, but he did not provide more details.
The final document also touched on the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to re-join the Union of South American Nations", from which she is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, to be united, and to have good relations among neighbors was another topic emphasized at the summit.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before he began attending the regional meeting that he hopes to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, in Mexico City on Saturday to negotiate in a respectful manner on the maritime dispute resulting from the verdict of the international court challenged by Bogotá.
"After tomorrow (Saturday), I may meet with President Daniel Ortega", Santos said.
"We will review all these ways, they are not mutually exclusive, including the pact with Nicaragua will require discussions with Nicaragua", he stressed.
"With President Ortega, I hope I can tell him that we will handle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible", Santos added.
Santos and Ortega will meet in Mexico City on Saturday, where they are scheduled to attend the inauguration of the country's new president, Enrique Pena Nieto.
Also at the summit, the bloc's defense ministers met in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which aims to strengthen dialogue and unity on the issue of protecting the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are all members of UNASUR, although the latter is suspended.
Peru has a provisional presidency in the regional bloc.
"South America should learn from Europe in the integration of citizenship": Rafael Correa
The President of Ecuador, Rafael Correa, confirmed today that the creation of a common citizenship is a goal in which "South America, in this case, yes, should learn from Europe".
Correa, who attended the VI Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) held in Lima, told Peru's state television that Europeans "killed each other during World War II" and other conflicts, "but now they are practically one homeland".
He defended, in this context, the project of establishing South American citizenship, which is approved by the UNASUR member countries.
"We need to achieve free movement of citizens and workers in any South American country, as is already happening with members of the Andean community, but there are still reactionary sectors that want to return us to the past", he warned.
The Ecuadorian president also expressed his support for the revival of the Organization of American States (OAS) under the condition that the Anglo-Saxon states' influence be reduced and that the San Jose Human Rights Pact be taken into account.
Those who give lectures never make any commitments, and we South Americans, on the contrary, sign everything.
"It is inexplicable that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights is based in Washington and funded by the United States", he said, referring to the political asylum granted by Ecuador to WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange.
Correa said he did not regret his decision, because he did not betray his principles, but he respected his "deep values of democracy and human rights".
He added that at the time "there were certain suspicions that Assange would be extradited to a third country and that the process would not be followed".
He also criticized the Swedish judiciary for requiring him to come to its territory for questioning regarding an alleged sexual offence, while "Swedish law itself considers it possible to do it via video conference, which could be done from the Ecuadorian embassy in London".
Correa confirmed that there was a risk of deterioration of Assange's physical and mental health.
"I haven't spoken to him since he arrived at our embassy, but the ambassador told me that he had a small lung problem, nothing serious", the Ecuadorian head of state said.
What really exists is the danger of deteriorating his physical and mental health by being confined in a small space without the possibility of exercising in the open air.
"It affects the health of any person", he added.
Correa pointed out that the solution to the asylum issue granted to Assange since June at the Ecuadorian embassy in London, through the granting of a guarantee of inviolability that would allow him to travel to Ecuador, is in the hands of the UK, Sweden and European judicial authorities, and stressed that there were negotiations in London to find a solution to the issue of imprisonment of the WikiLeaks founder.
We don't negotiate human rights, we don't use that word in this case, but there have been constant discussions.
"The solution to this problem is in the hands of the UK, Sweden and the European judiciary, because Assange's lawyer, Baltasar Garson, is leading a number of trials in various European courts", he said.
And he expressed the opinion that "if Britain gives a guarantee of immunity tomorrow, this will be over".
And if Sweden, as it is perfectly permitted by its legislation and as it has done in other cases, interrogates Mr. Assange at the Ecuadorian embassy in London or interrogates him via Skype, tomorrow the problem will be exhausted.
Correa took the opportunity to present himself as a defender of press freedom and stressed that he does not tolerate "mediation, dishonesty and lies that distort freedom of expression".
"The main enemies of press freedom are not corrupt political villains, but bad journalists who support profit, blackmail and extortion", he said.
In this aspect, he remained satisfied that neither these journalists, "nor the bankers, nor the bourgeois hegemon countries dominate Ecuador", and added that being re-elected, "will deepen the revolution to continue development in the right direction".
Correa also supported the decision to keep Paraguay's veto in UNASUR at least until the next election, arguing that the organization "must be firm and not tolerate opportunism and supporting coups under the guise of legality", because in reality "it has destroyed the legality of Paraguayan democracy".
The Ecuadorian president also considered "absolutely justified" the desire of his Colombian counterpart Juan Manuel Santos to negotiate now with Nicaragua on the maritime borders between the two countries after the decision of the International Court of Justice of the Hague, which was in favor of Nicaragua's maritime sovereignty.
At the moment, this decision is not being followed.
This is a problem between the countries of South and Central America.
Conflict is inevitable, but it must be overcome by the desire to walk together.
We need to work through them together to get over them and keep moving forward.
He also expressed hope for a successful conclusion of the maritime border dispute between Peru and Chile, which is being tried in the same court, and said that "it is right for Latin America to appeal to international bodies if the two countries commit to a decision, however difficult it may be".
Regarding the possibility of running for the upcoming presidential election in Ecuador, to run for a third consecutive term, he indicated that he is looking at this opportunity "with great optimism and joy, although sometimes it is quite difficult".
Correa has said that if he loses the February 2013 elections, he will withdraw from public life.
Personally, I've never been interested in power, but in situations of injustice like Ecuador, socioeconomic poverty can only be corrected by political power.
"My political movement felt that I was the one who guaranteed this probable victory, so I have to accept that responsibility", he said.
If I win, it would be my last term as president, and then we're out of public life.
If we lose, the same thing.
"It's a decision", he confirmed.
Correa also mentioned the new treatment of Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez in Cuba.
I just spoke to Venezuelan Vice President Nicolas Maduro, who told me that he went for treatment, which was already scheduled, routine, and that he was expected to miss the campaign to return to Cuba.
"This does not mean that President Chavez's health is deteriorating", he explained.
