Today 's AIDS deaths are the result of late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was told that his test for AIDS had tested positive.
"I felt deaf", he recalls, "despite all the doctor's tact, that difficult moment.
The young man hid it from his family.
Deciding to deal with his illness on his own, he wanted to learn as much as he could about it, and his efforts paid off - he had already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
Fabrizio is one of the "oldest" HIV patients at the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), where he arrived in 1994 after overcoming many obstacles.
He's been living with the human immunodeficiency virus for 22 years, and in the early '90s, it would have been hard to believe, because there were so few treatment options, so little knowledge about the disease, so much prejudice toward patients.
Even the director of the Mexican Institute of Social Security did not want to say goodbye to him "because he had a cut".
In other words, having AIDS was a death sentence in those days.
Now it's possible to survive with this syndrome and do it without compromising quality of life.
However, many people still come, not knowing they have the disease, when the virus has already done damage, depleted their immune system, and they suffer from opportunistic infections.
31 years after the world's first reported cases of AIDS, "the greatest achievement so far is that the survival rate of patients who start treatment on time is exactly the same as the general population", said HCG's head of HIV, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, referring to the fact that this information was confirmed in April this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectionist and HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva explained that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is not a death sentence, but that life expectancy and quality of life depend on the degree of immune system damage patients have at the start of diagnosis, with the best life expectancy for those who do not use drugs: up to 30 years with 200 CD4s, and up to 50 years when 500 CD4s are reported.
Simply put, this means that a person diagnosed HIV-positive at age 25, in these terms, "with control, can live comfortably until age 75", he explained.
To gauge this progress, remember that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although mortality has declined significantly in recent years, in Mexico's case, the number of people dying from AIDS has dropped from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (the annual report of UNAIDS), and it is also true that since the onset of AIDS, 60 percent of the patients in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and 187 deaths have been recorded as of May of this year; however, it is claimed that there has been widespread access to antiretroviral drugs since 2005.
- Why are there still deaths?
- Personally, I don't think the problem is access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's how things are at our hospital.
We haven't had a shortage of medicines for at least the last 12 years, and the problem is that patients come in very late because they don't know they're infected, so they're in the late stages.
He quoted the devastating data: "Nine out of ten patients come in with some opportunistic infection already; what needs to be done to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to do early diagnosis, and therefore provide mass screening for all people who ask".
The proposal is shared by experts and officials of the State Council for the Prevention of AIDS in Jalisco (COESIDA), as well as patients like Fabrizio, who went to a private laboratory for testing, motivated only by the fact that his friend did it and, despite his young age, he was already at the stage of AIDS and even suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancer tumor, which is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die, and they don't want to know.
"If I die, I'd rather get a three-a-week blow job", they say, but not me.
There are positive changes, I eat well, I exercise, I take medication.
To this day, all his parents know is that he had cancer.
I live a normal life like everyone else.
"I work, I have a lot of things to do, I travel, I have an active sex life, but with mutual responsibility, I take care of myself and the other person", said Fabrizio, who agreed to share his personal life with MILENIO JALISCO to encourage those who are now afraid in the context of World AIDS Day.
Let them know if they've been tested, if they've been at risk, if they're HIV positive as soon as possible, that's better, and if they've been diagnosed, let them know that they can live like everyone else, responsibly.
This is his message summarizing the theme of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms are on the counter .
There is a huge gap between health programs and the average citizen, says Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has covered the HIV problem.
And the biggest one is prevention.
In places dedicated to this, "the prevalence of condoms has actually increased, we used to get one or two, now we get a hundred packs, and that's great, but it turns out there are still people who don't have access to condoms", he said.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
"Why do you need them?" is a popular question, with both jeering and condemnation from social workers, school counselors, pharmacy workers and health workers who don't want to hear from teenagers, the promoter assured.
I propose changing this inefficient distribution; that condoms not only be behind the counter, but that there be hundreds in vending machines in public toilets in places that young people frequent.
It's not a promotion of promiscuity.
It's not about paying for beer and a motel, said Governor Emilio González when asked if condoms could be distributed under his leadership.
"It's not sexuality, it's best to make condoms available to those who are already sexually active", he said.
Key data in the Jalisco
A total of 13,435 cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV) were recorded .
The state ranks fourth nationally in new and total AIDS cases and 13th in HIV.
Ninety-two percent of infections are from the genital tract, six percent from the bloodstream, and two percent from the perinatal tract.
It is estimated that 50,000 people may be living with HIV, because there are four to five people for every recorded case who are unaware of it.
