Hector "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
The avid basketball traveler Hector "Hetin" Reyes has been involved with the sport for over 60 years and has traveled the world.
Few Puerto Ricans have as many basketball stories as Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
And before a brain hemorrhage confined him to a wheelchair in 2008, Reyes had been immersed in the sport for more than 60 years, as a minor leaguer, a Major League Baseball player, commissioner and executive of the BSN with the Bayamon Cowboys and president of the Basketball Federation.
"I've played many roles in basketball throughout my life, including several at the same time, like when I was president of BSN, general manager of the National Team and president of the federation in the '90s", Reyes recalled during a Primera Hora visit to his home in Bayamon, where he lives with Isabel, his faithful wife of more than 50 years.
"Basketball was my life".
Reyes is not exaggerating when he makes that statement.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photographs and memorabilia gathered during his long journey, testify to this.
Bayamon in the heart
He holds the most emotion for those who remember his journey through the Cowboys, from the mid-'50s as a player to 1982, when it was 15 years since he was a co-agent or contract agent.
"These were my best years, which I enjoyed the most, because I've had the opportunity to be a part of eight Cowboy championships since 1967, as an agent, co-agent or manager.
There were many years of joy, including five championships held from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye to one in 1981, the year Jerome Mincy debuted on BSN.
From that moment on, "Cuko" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, became the leader", Reyes said.
I remember Gene Bartow, who was on his way here, and he was at the University of Alabama, Birmingham, and he said, "I have a very strong player for you, 6'7".
"Do you want to?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico had.
Bartoff then recommended sniper Raymond Gauss, who became a naturalized citizen and one of our best bombers.
I remember saying that if Mincy brought the championship to Bayamon, Gauss would help win another one.
I enjoyed the Cowboy championship with Gauss, but I was already at a distance, because by 1988 I was already the head of the federation.
By then I'd preferred to enjoy his achievements and Minci's achievements in the national team.
I remember when we first won for the U.S. during the Olympic qualifying tournament in Mexico in 1989.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we finished fourth and it should have been bronze, if not for the Canadian referee who made us win the final game, Reyes said.
That 1990 World Cup team is the best team you've ever seen?
She's one of the best, just like the one that won the 2004 Olympic Dream Team.
But my favorite was the one from the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba, when we won gold and beat the U.S. team, which was pretty similar to the one that won us bronze at the World Championships.
In that team not only played again Minsi, Gaussa, Ramona Rivas, Fico Lopez and 'Piculina' (Ortiz), but also young (Xavier) 'Tonito' Colón and James Carter, brothers Leon (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario 'Kihote' Morales, who could not participate in 90 due to a knee injury.
The team that may not have been the best in terms of personnel, but that brought us the gold medal and the great joy, was the team of the 1995 Olympic qualifying tournament in Neuquen, Argentina.
With the likes of Canito Nieves, Pablo Alise and a young Rolando Hurruitner in exchange for players suspended for disorderly conduct at the Pan American Mar del Plata, we won gold against all odds.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
Without a doubt, it was Piculin Ortiz.
His performances at international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has ever dominated at this level like Piculin did.
And that's not counting his career in the various leagues he played in.
Who was the best Puerto Rican manager?
That's a very complicated question.
We had a very good young man, including Julio Toro, Flora Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armando Torres.
From a young age, I really like Leo Arilla's work.
What do you consider your greatest accomplishment in the Federation?
Participating in the most glorious era of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and that in the early 90s in BSN there were up to 17 teams in a season.
What's left for you to do?
There were things I wanted to do, like regionalising smaller categories.
Like the Ponce boys playing only in their area and only against teams from other parts of the island in the national playoffs.
Kids travel and play too much these days, and it's unnecessary.
At least I see the fruits of mandatory certification and coursework for administrators, officials and judges.
It gives me pleasure.
What are you doing now?
Mostly I listen to music, watch music videos from my era on YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren, and occasionally go to basketball games.
